=== Preamble

Alchemical work is individual work. The community structures of this Academy exist to support the intellectual, philosophical, and operative dimensions of shared study — not to substitute for any professional service or to create personal advisory relationships. The following agreements describe both the character this community aspires to maintain and the minimum ethical baseline required for safe participation.

=== Part One — Conduct Within the Community

*Honesty:* Students report on their practical work honestly, including failures, confusions, and difficulties. The alchemical tradition regards the distinction between genuine results and what the imagination supplies as fundamental. Exaggeration of results, fabrication of experiences, or performance of attainment undermines the shared inquiry and may mislead other students.

*Respect:* Students engage with each other and with Guides with basic courtesy. Philosophical disagreement is welcome. Contempt, condescension, manipulation, and coercion are not.

*Confidentiality:* What is shared in Gatherings or in Guide conversations is held in confidence. Students do not repeat the personal disclosures of other students outside the community. This confidentiality does not extend to disclosures suggesting imminent risk of harm to self or others; Guides exercise judgment in such cases per the Crisis-Response SOP and Guide Code of Conduct.

*No unsolicited advice:* Students do not offer medical, psychological, legal, or financial advice to other students or to their Guides. When a fellow student appears to be struggling, the appropriate response is to encourage them toward appropriate professional support.

*No proselytising:* The alchemical tradition encompasses a wide range of philosophical and spiritual orientations. Students do not pressure others to adopt their views, practices, or interpretations.

=== Part Two — The Guide Relationship

Guides are Educational Facilitators who have completed the three-year curriculum. The Guide relationship is an educational facilitation relationship — not a therapeutic, mentoring, pastoral, or personal advisory relationship.

==== What Guides Do

- Support engagement with curriculum content: readings, laboratory methods, inner work practices, and symbolic frameworks
- Schedule and participate in quarterly check-in sessions
- Review student journal submissions for curriculum completeness
- Coordinate safety assessment processes (Safety Quiz, photo verification)
- Signpost students toward appropriate professional resources when personal difficulties arise
- Follow the Crisis-Response SOP when a student discloses signs of crisis

==== What Guides Do Not Do

- Assess or advise on any student's psychological health, mental state, or emotional wellbeing
- Provide medical advice, health information, or recommendations regarding any preparation
- Conduct crisis counselling, suicide risk assessment, or any form of clinical support
- Offer legal or financial advice
- Serve as personal mentors, life coaches, sponsors, or spiritual directors
- Accept, handle, or facilitate the transfer of any preparation from any student
- Recommend for or against any student's personal use of any preparation

Guides do not have authority to waive, modify, or grant exceptions to any requirement in any Safety Document.

